    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 3.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n* **S \u2013 Set the Stage (The Verdict & Diagnostic Pivot)**\n\u2028Verdict: Correct: B. Rupture of the renal capsule or the presence of tumor spillage will upgrade the tumor stage.\n\u2028The Pivot: Under both the NWTSG/COG and SIOP staging systems for Wilms tumor (nephroblastoma), any intraoperative tumor rupture or spillage automatically upgrades the disease to Stage III, requiring changes to the postoperative treatment plan.\n* **H \u2013 Highlight Excellence (The Surgical \"Why\" & Pathology)**\n  * **Surgical Mechanism:** Wilms tumor is a delicate embryonic tumor derived from metanephric blastema cells. The tumor is enclosed by a renal capsule and Gerota's fascia. If the capsule ruptures during surgery, tumor cells spill into the peritoneal cavity. This transforms a localized disease into one with a high risk of diffuse peritoneal seeding, necessitating the addition of abdominal radiation therapy to control local recurrence.\n  * **Clinical Execution:** During a radical nephrectomy for a Wilms tumor, surgeons use a wide transperitoneal approach to achieve complete control of the renal vessels before manipulating the mass. Every effort is made to remove the tumor en bloc with its surrounding fat and Gerota's fascia intact. If a rupture occurs, the site must be thoroughly irrigated, the area documented, and the patient's staging upgraded to Stage III to initiate postoperative flank or whole-abdomen radiation alongside multi-agent chemotherapy.\n* **A \u2013 Address the Gaps (Systematic Distractor Demolition)**\n  * **Distractor Breakdown:**\n\u2028Option A (Incorrect): Preoperative chemotherapy (the SIOP approach) typically shrinks the tumor and hardens its pseudocapsule, decreasing the risk of intraoperative rupture during surgical handling rather than increasing it.\n\u2028Option C (Incorrect): Gerota\u2019s fascia must be removed en bloc with the kidney tumor; leaving it untouched violates oncologic principles and increases the risk of positive margins and recurrence.\n\u2028Option D (Incorrect): Peritoneal soiling or tumor spillage upgrades the disease to Stage III (not Stage II), which modifies the treatment plan by requiring abdominal radiation therapy.\n* **R \u2013 Review Learning Points (Evidence-Based Framework)**\n\u2028Conceptual Overview: Staging for Wilms tumor is based on whether the capsule remains intact and whether the tumor can be completely removed without local contamination.\n  * **Classification / Management Framework:**\nNWTSG / COG Wilms Stage\nPathological Extension Criteria\nTumor Spillage Status\nPostoperative Management Pivot\nStage I\nLimited to kidney; intact capsule\nAbsent\nRoutine chemotherapy; no radiation\nStage II\nExtends beyond kidney but completely resected\nAbsent\nRoutine chemotherapy; no radiation\n\nStage III\nResidual tumor, positive nodes, or capsule breach\n\nPresent (Local or Diffuse)\nAdd Abdominal Radiation Therapy + Intensified Chemotherapy\nStage IV\nHematogenous metastases (Lung, Liver)\nVariable\nSystemic chemotherapy + Local therapies\n* **P \u2013 Plan for Improvement (The Exam Heuristic)**\n\u2028The Board Pearl: Remember that any intraoperative rupture, capsule breach, or fluid spillage during a Wilms tumor resection automatically upgrades the patient to Stage III, which requires adding postoperative abdominal radiation therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Supplementary Callouts\n> **Society Guideline**\n> Children's Oncology Group (COG) guidelines state that if a Wilms tumor ruptures during surgery, the patient must be managed under Stage III protocols, receiving abdominal radiation within 10\u201314 days of surgery to optimize local control.\n> **Key Takeaway**\n> Intraoperative tumor rupture or capsule breach upgrades a Wilms tumor to Stage III, requiring the addition of postoperative abdominal radiation.\n> **Intraoperative / Imaging Visualization**\n> In the operating room, the surgeon inspects the tumor capsule throughout the dissection; if a tear occurs, the area is marked with surgical clips to help the radiation oncologist accurately target the postoperative radiation field."
